{
  "texts": [
    "But in practice, it cannot be used, because",
    "] is of course unknown (still, we use the prior π -βR in Section 4 below, in theoretical bounds that are not meant to be evaluated on the data).",
    "For empirical bounds, Catoni proved that KL (ρ∥π -βR) can be upper bounded, with large probability, by KL (ρ∥π -ξr) for ξ = β/(λ + g(λ/n)λ 2 /n), plus some additional terms (g being Bernstein's function defined in Lemma 3.8).",
    "Plugging this result into Theorem 2.1, he obtained the following \"localized bound\" (Catoni, 2003, Lemma 6.2):",
    "which means that we are allowed to use π -ξr, that is data-dependent, as a prior!"
  ]
}